For {= agency =}+ demand-generation, media, marketing-operations, partner-channel, paid-media, ABM, CRM/lifecycle, adtech/martech-services, or closely adjacent marketing agencies/service providers, cover {= partner_program =}+ public platform/program partner relationships per agency; for each agency-program relationship and each of the {= reference_type =} relationship sides below, supply a relationship-substantiating source (i.e. {= url =}+ URL). The agency identity includes both a public agency name and an official domain so same-name agencies remain distinct.

The useful object is neutral public provenance for agency-program relationships and public discovery profiles, not supplier quality, ranking, procurement fit, outreach, or contactability.

The relationship sides of interest, which we refer to as `reference_type`, are:
- `agency_claim`: an agency-owned, agency-controlled, or official agency-channel statement naming the platform/program relationship. A platform/program-hosted partner directory, marketplace, profile, listing, or program page does not satisfy `agency_claim` for that relationship, even when it contains agency-supplied profile copy; that source belongs under `program_listing`.
- `program_listing`: a platform/program-controlled agency-specific public profile, detail page, listing entry, marketplace, or directory page independently naming or describing the agency in that program context.

Agencies ought to be real marketing service firms or agency-like service providers, not pure software products, contact-enrichment databases, publishers/media owners, staffing firms, in-house brand teams, individual freelancers without an agency organization, generic list publishers, or placeholders. `partner_program` ought to be a real martech, adtech, media, CRM, advertising, analytics, partner-channel, or adjacent marketing-technology platform/program, not another agency, a client logo, a generic media channel, or an internal service label. Sources ought to be public, accessible, and usable; generic search or result pages, broad directory home pages without an agency-specific entry, login-only pages, contact-enrichment profiles, paid contact directories, and unrelated careers/staff pages do not provide the public relationship evidence sought here.

Requirements:
- The page should communicate that it is controlled by the relationship side being cited: for `agency_claim`, an agency-owned, agency-controlled, or official agency-channel surface, not a platform/program-hosted directory, marketplace, profile, or listing for that same relationship; for `program_listing`, a platform/program-owned, platform/program-controlled, or officially program-hosted surface.
- The page must explicitly identify the opposite party and the public partner/program relationship. For `agency_claim`, the agency should name the platform, program, certification, badge, marketplace, or partner status. For `program_listing`, the platform/program surface should name the agency in a public listing, profile, marketplace, or directory context. Vague references to "marketing platforms" or "certified partners" do not count without a named opposite party.
- The page should expose agency/program substance appropriate to `reference_type`: for `agency_claim`, source-stated certification, tier, badge, service relationship, platform-specific capability, or similar partner-status substance; for `program_listing`, an agency-specific listing/profile/detail page or listing entry with visible detail such as service category, specialty, region, certification/tier, partner type, managed-service role, customer objective, or comparable program-context detail. Generic search/result pages and card-only list pages without enough agency-specific relationship detail do not count.
